findingsText:
 The project increased our understanding of how the multi-cellular nature of biological systems and their
protective immune systems could be used to enhance reliability of digital electronic systems, focusing especially on innate and acquired immune responses, and on incorporating these 'nature/like' fault-tolerance mechanisms into engineering systems.

In particular the project:

(i) Produce an implementation of fundamental cells with intrinsic self-repairing mechanisms;
(ii) Used ideas from prokaryotic cells to create a new design approach based on cooperating cell groups;
(iii) Used the combination of an innate and acquired immune system to supervise the self-repairing architecture;
(iv) Used FPGA (Field Programmable Gate Array) to implement a number of demonstrators to illustrate the
capabilities of the system in a robot application scenario. The outcomes of the project were a novel set of methods and techniques to design and implement more reliable hardware structures and ultimately devices. In this regard future developments of these ideas could be integrated into special VLSI devices for ultra-high reliability applications. Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Digital/Communication/Information Technologies (including Software),Electronics,Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology
